Polish Stocks: Azoty, Globe Trade, Lotos, Orlen, Pekao, Slaski

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i
-- 
2011-08-22T12:31:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-22/polish-stocks-azoty-globe-trade-lotos-orlen-pekao-slaski.html
Poland ’s WIG20 Index rose for a
second day, increasing 37.19, or 1.7 percent, to 2,289.59 at
2:19 p.m. in Warsaw.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
 Warsaw Stock Exchange  today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Azoty Tarnow (ATT PW) jumped 1.8 zloty, or 6.2 percent, to
30.8 zloty, heading for the highest close since July 27. The
chemical producer that bought a majority stake in domestic
competitor Zaklady Chemiczne Police SA this month said first-
half profit soared to 187.9 million zloty ($65 million) from
29.8 million zloty a year earlier.  Globe Trade Centre SA (GTC)   fell 0.26 zloty, or 2.1
percent, to 12.02 zloty, heading for the lowest close since
February 2009. Poland’s biggest property developer by market
value said its second-quarter loss widened to 185.4 million
zloty from 4.68 million zloty a year earlier.  ING Bank Slaski SA (BSK)   rose for the first time in
three days, climbing 20 zloty, or 2.9 percent, to 710.5 zloty as
the ING Groep NV unit was upgraded to “buy” from “sell” at
Citigroup Inc.  PKN Orlen SA (PKN PW) jumped 2.11 zloty, or 6.1 percent, to
36.92 zloty, heading for the biggest gain since April 1 and
 Grupa Lotos SA (LTS)  , the second-largest refiner, advanced
1.12 zloty, or 3.5 percent, to 33.5 zloty as crude oil
rebounded.  Bank Pekao SA (PEO)   added as much as 1.5 percent to
131.5 zloty and last traded 0.5 percent higher at 130.3 zloty,
extending its 5 percent increase on Aug. 19. Poland’s second-
largest bank had its price estimate increased to 190 zloty from
186 zloty at Citigroup.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Pawel Kozlowski in Warsaw 
